Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year pushed all its students to sleep more in an attempt to counteract the growing virile culture of studying for whole nights powered by caffeine.
One university scholar noted that students at the world's number one university often have no idea of the basic concepts of taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, developed the course, which he believes to be the first of its kind in the USA.
She had the idea of starting the course after a lecture she had given on the impact of lack of sleep on learning.
"In the end a girl came to me and said to me, 'Why is this told to me just now, when I'm a senior?'
He said that no one had ever told her anything about the importance of sleep, which surprised me very much," he told The Telegraph.
The course, first given this year, explains to students the essential concepts of how good sleep habits can help academic and athletic performance, as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and general director of the university's health services, stated that the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students suffered from a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive activities.
In one section there is the image of a dorm room, where students can select cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep, and the importance of an evening routine.
In another section, participants are explained how the lack of long-term sleep can increase the risks of heart attacks, stroke, depression and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive icons, therefore encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that it will not change the behavior of the students immediately.
But we believe that they are entitled to know, just as one has the right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes," added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride linked to the "white night to study", still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the increasing pressure on students lead the lack of sleep to be a growing problem.
Sleeping enough and with a good quality sleep should be the "secret weapon" of students to combat stress, fatigue, anxiety, he explained and even should serve to avoid fattening since the lack of sleep brings the brain into a state of starvation, making people constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student enrolled in the Faculty of Chemical and Physical Biology, helped Professor Czeisler develop the course, after attending one of his lectures last year during his first year at Harvard.
He explained that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course aimed at the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, will be to ask all graduate students to follow a similar curriculum before enrolling in this competitive institute.
Professor Czeisler advised students to set an alarm clock for when they have to go to bed, as well as for when they have to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can tilt the circadian rhythm, leading to sleep problems.
