The National Trust spyes on the secret life of bats
New research carried out in a Scottish Highland estate aims to reveal the way bats use sight to procure food.
It is hoped that discoveries can shed light on the behavior of the only flying mammals in existence and guide future protection activities.
The study of the scientists of the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and soprano, as well as brown mumps and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens, in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key places around the property to track the activities of bats during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys with the use of portable detectors.
Analysis of sounds recorded by an expert will determine the frequency of bat calls and the way each species behaves.
A habitat map and a report will then be produced to create a detailed picture of their behaviour on a scale.
Rob Dewar, a nature protection consultant for the NTS, hopes that the results can reveal which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how these are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of meadows, and how best to maintain forests for bats and other related species.
The population of bats in Scotland and the United Kingdom has decreased considerably in the last century.
Bats are at risk due to construction and development work affecting trespolis and ruining the habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a threat, as can flypaper and some chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than the eyes when it comes to grabbing a prey.
They use a sophisticated eco-location technique to detect insects and obstacles on their trajectory.
The NTS, responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
Ten qualified experts conduct regular investigations, inspect the trespolis and sometimes carry out rescues.
The organization has even established Scotland's first reserve intended solely for bats at the Threeve estate, in the Dumfries and Galloway region, which houses eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The manager of the estate, David Thompson, states that the property is the ideal territory.
"Here in Threeve we have a large area for bats," he said.
"We have ancient buildings, many secular trees and a good habitat.
But there's a lot about bats we don't know yet, so the work we do here and in the other properties will help us to understand more about their growth needs."
It underlines the importance of controlling bats before conducting maintenance within the properties as it is possible that the unintended destruction of a single maternal trespole can kill up to 400 females and small, perhaps wiping out an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, harass them, disturb them or destroy their trespolises.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
He said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species we don't know how their populations are going through it."
